<font color="#FF0000">NO ONE WAS IMMUNE......</font><br>
<tt>Thu Nov 20  0:42:35 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I came back home physically intact and, so I thought, emotionally intact as well. I discovered that my memories of Naval Air assistance with the war were sketchy at best <br>
and for the most part not worth remembering. I entered the US Navy in 1963, green, raw, and unaware.<br>
I made several WestPac tours and enjoyed letting my hair down in several ports. The philippines was always my favorite. I enjoyed the food, culture and the people. I was <br>
ecstatic when I received orders to Cubi Pt. From there I went to Japan and then the US.<br>
After many bitter experiences with the US Navy, my wife, (then), mandatory psychiatric care, forced medication, and many other minor irritants, I decided enough is enough.<br>
I demanded a summary court martial and accepted an honorable discharge after nearly 10 years of service in SE Asia.<br>
I went through the next twenty some years, feeling very grateful for not having been subjected to the Vietnam experience. But, I felt lost. I didn't know what I should be doing other than trying to locate my daughter, who was being hidden from me. During all of this time there was always a nagging thought at the back of my mind. &quot;There is something that I am supposed to do.&quot; I did not know what that something was or even how to discover it.<br>
On October 2 1997 I received a letter from the VA in San Diego. Inside was a type written note that stated, &quot;This person wishes to correspond with you. Your address has <br>
not been given to the person. Any action you take on this matter is entirely up to you.&quot; Also enclosed was a hand written letter dated May 20, 1997 that stated; &quot;Dear Mr. <br>
Ballenger  Hello! Maybe you'll be surprised upon receiving this letter. First I want to introduce myself.  I am (name withheld), 27 years old. I was born Dec. 9, 1969 in <br>
Olongapo City. My mother's name is (withheld) and according to my mother, my father's name is Robert L. Ballenger, who was stationed at Cubi Pt. The only souvenir he left was <br>
his laundry bag with letters and numbers VA-115 &amp; ATR2 that is in my possession to this time. He also left a small picture with the number  686-12-26 on it. If you remember or <br>
know about any of this information, please let me know and write a letter with some old and recent photos that I can compare with. Ever since I was a small child, it has ben my <br>
most important dream and wish to someday meet and know my father.  THANK YOU and I hope for your response.   Respectfully Yours   Bernadette Ballenger&quot;<br>
Memories started pouring into my mind as in a flood of images, emotions, anger, rage. <br>
Incomplete as the memories were, I knew this was my daughter from the deepest part of my gut, I knew. I promised her, while an infant, and her mother that I would return for <br>
them. I had loved her mother more than any other woman on this earth. AND THAT LOVE WAS NOW PRESENT. What happened??? Where were my memories? How could I have forgotten? Why had I forgotten?? More emotions flowed within me. GUILT  <br>
How could my little girl be erased from my memory? She was not an accident. Her mother and I had planned her birth.<br>
Back to the main theme of this site. I thought I had come out of the war very fortunate with no nightmares, no thoughts that I could not voice. As I was soon to discover, I was not alone. It took awhile but I remembered friends, buddies, that I could not even remember names or faces before. I found one of my closest friends. He had gone through similar circumstances for nearly 30 years as well.<br>
Both of us now, to fill in more gaps of memory, need to find James Benson. Jim is from Nebraska. He has a tattoo on his left arm &quot;Jim&quot;<br>
If from a support facility, this has happened to the few I am aware of,,,, how many more are there that have had major portions of their lives ripped from them?<br>
